        <p data-uuid="8e0cf19105ee4d878c5f1d01e2c73ee6">Wisely, the delegates at the First Continental Congress compromised. They encouraged colonists to continue boycotting British goods but told colonial militias to prepare for war. Meanwhile, they drafted the Declaration of Rights, a list of ten resolutions to be presented to King George III. Included in the document was a proclamation of the colonists’ right to “life, liberty, and property.”</p>
        <p data-uuid="b54b123c0d424d2f89686539de0f383a"> The First Continental Congress did not seek a separation from Britain. Its goal was to state the colonists’ concerns and ask the king to correct the problems. But before they left Philadelphia, the delegates agreed to meet in 1775 if the king refused their petition.</p>
        <p data-uuid="91a3e86ac2bc43e7a32d9e7011b768b9">In time many colonists came to agree with Henry. They became known as <b><dfn title="Patriots">Patriots</dfn></b>—colonists who chose to fight for independence from Great Britain.</p>
